The paper discusses statistical models for social networks and their application in social science research. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Social and Information Retrieval (cs.SI) or Social and Information Networks (cs.SOC) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of statistical methods for understanding the structured nature of social life, which could also place it in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) or Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the effect of using sampled network data, which could place it in the Cybersecurity (cs.CYBER) sub-category.
